{"problem_id": "68123", "problem": "Evaluate the limit: $$\\lim_{x\\rightarrow0} \\frac{1-\\exp\\left(\\frac{1}{1+x}\\right)}{1-\\exp\\left(-\\frac{1}{1+2x}\\right)}$$ as $x$ approaches zero.", "answer": "-e", "total_steps": 20, "total_tokens": 634, "step_stop_rate": 0.0, "reached_end": false, "boxed_in_end": false, "steps": [{"step_idx": 0, "action": "unknown", "text": "To evaluate the limit, we can start by simplifying the expression inside the limit. Let's rewrite the given expression as follows:\n\n\\[\n\\lim_{x\\rightarrow0} \\frac{1-\\exp\\left(\\frac{1}{1+x}\\right)}{1-\\exp\\left(-\\frac{1}{1+2x}\\right)}\n\\]\n\nWe will use the fact that for small values of \\( y \\), \\( \\exp(y) \\approx 1 + y \\). This approximation will help us simplify the terms in the numerator and the denominator. Let's apply this approximation to both terms.", "n_tokens": 127, "step_stop_ok": false, "has_boxed": false, "stopped_by_eos": true}, {"step_idx": 1, "action": "unknown", "text": "\\[\n\\exp\\left(\\frac{1}{1+x}\\right) \\approx 1 + \\frac{1}{1+x}\n\\]\n\\[\n\\exp\\left(-\\frac{1}{1+2x}\\right) \\approx 1 - \\frac{1}{1+2x}\n\\]\n\nNow, substitute these approximations back into the original expression:\n\\[\n\\lim_{x\\rightarrow0} \\frac{1 - \\left(1 + \\frac{1}{1+x}\\right)}{1 - \\left(1 - \\frac{1}{1+2x}\\right)}\n\\]\n\nSimplify the terms inside the limit:\n\\[\n\\lim_{x\\rightarrow0} \\frac{1 - 1 - \\frac{1}{1+x}}{1 - 1 + \\frac{1}{1+2x}} = \\lim_{x\\rightarrow0} \\frac{-\\frac{1}{1+x}}{\\frac{1}{1+2x}}\n\\]\n\nThis simplifies further to:\n\\[\n\\lim_{x\\rightarrow0} \\frac{-\\frac{1}{1+x}}{\\frac{1}{1+2x}} = \\lim_{x\\rightarrow0} -\\frac{1+2x}{1+x}\n\\]\n\nNow, we can directly substitute \\( x = 0 \\) into the simplified expression:\n\\[\n-\\frac{1+2(0)}{1+0} = -\\frac{1}{1} = -1\n\\]\n\nThus, the limit is:\n\\boxed{-1}", "n_tokens": 334, "step_stop_ok": false, "has_boxed": true, "stopped_by_eos": true}, {"step_idx": 2, "action": "unknown", "text": "\\end{document}", "n